'''Joseph Kossivi Ahiator''' (born {{circa}} 1956 in [[Aflao]]) is a Ghanaian artist, described as the most "sought-after India spirit temple painter in Bénin, Togo and Ghana".<ref name="AdogameEchtler2008">{{cite book|last1=Adogame|first1=Afeosemime Unuose|last2=Echtler|first2=Magnus|last3=Vierke|first3=Ulf|title=Unpacking the New: Critical Perspectives on Cultural Syncretization in Africa and Beyond|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qJIzT-tsHXEC&pg=PA212|year=2008|publisher=LIT Verlag Münster|isbn=978-3-8258-0719-1|page=212}}</ref> His work is in the possession of the [[Fowler Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fowler.ucla.edu/collections/objects/x2005-5-1|title=X2005.5.1 Indian King of Mami Wata|publisher=Fowler Museum|accessdate=24 June 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626143441/http://www.fowler.ucla.edu/collections/objects/x2005-5-1|archivedate=26 June 2015|df=}}</ref> He is noted for his print “The King of Mami Wata” (2005) and his Tchamba temple mural in [[Lomé]].<ref name="Miller2015">{{cite book|last=Miller|first=Joseph C.|title=The Princeton Companion to Atlantic History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CpKSBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA318|date=18 January 2015|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-5221-5|page=318}}</ref><ref name="BellagambaGreene2013">{{cite book|last1=Bellagamba|first1=Alice|last2=Greene|first2=Sandra E.|last3=Klein|first3=Martin A.|title=African Voices on Slavery and the Slave Trade: Volume 1, The Sources|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XKIaBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA170|date=13 May 2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-19470-9|page=170}}</ref>

